He as in josh green. It would take some unforeseen jump that most players aren’t capable of making until they find a new environment that better suits them.
Considering all those circumstances, what are the odds he breaks out for the mavs? Doesn’t look too good.

Siakam was in a great development environment and showed more promise than green is rn and got a lot more opportunity. By the time DeJounte Murray was getting opportunities the spurs were falling off. Donte DiVincenzo improved his offensive capability rapidly.

Grew into a role and replaced Dwight Howard and got a lot of opportunity as Howard was aging. Nurkic got way more opportunities than josh. For all of Terry rozier’s moments he still made a ton of improvement in Charlotte, not Boston. Delon didn’t struggle as much as green.

Andre Roberson had a specialty skill on a team full of offensive talent. Dennis Schröder took off in his 2nd year in a manner that seems unlikely for green. Kyle Anderson was in a better development environment. Bogdan didn’t come over from Europe for several years. Capela..

Reggie Jackson still had more opportunity than josh is likely to get. The bulls fell off quickly with mirotic. Terrence Jones improved quickly but the depth of that rockets team at pf was questionable. Reggie bullock didn’t break out until his 3rd team, years down the line.

And had more opportunity, not to mention a great environment. Ryan Anderson got traded and immediately was used better with his skill set. Jeff Teague improved in his 2nd year and got more opportunities than josh likely gets. Jimmy butler immediately improved at an outlier rate.

Kyle Lowry didn’t break out until he left. Tiago splitter got a lot of opportunity and was in a great development system and still showed more promise early on. Jared Dudley showed some promise early but really broke out after he was traded. George hill showed more promise..

Improved and showed way more promise than green did in his rookie year. Delfino didn’t really break out until he left detroit. Kevin Martin improved rapidly and the kings were falling off. Dorrell Wright didn’t get much opportunity in Miami until the year Wade was hurt.

Speedy claxton was a journeyman player. He got traded immediately after his rookie year and broke out for a couple Alright years later on. Gerald Wallace didn’t break out until he left Sacramento. John salmons team fell out of playoff contention rapidly. Tayshaun prince rapidly..

Go down the line of non lottery first round picks in ~ last 20 years who were projects on teams seeking deep playoff runs & had or added significant depth at their position within the first 2 years. How many of those players ended up breaking out for the team that drafted them?

@MavsDraft Like I don’t care about the player itself you’re comparing to. I’m saying those guys circumstances and most other successes are not the ones green is facing. It’s going to be a lot more challenging for him to succeed here, so fans are upset. As they should be.
@MavsDraft I agree. I just don’t see how it can happen in this development context until something changes that can’t easily be predicted. Because the environment is currently very much unfavorable.

@MavsDraft it took Stephenson till his 3rd year to be a consistent player, then he had a really great year, then he got traded & he really hasn’t been the same since. Even if josh reaches Stephenson’s 3rd year level in his 3rd year, he won’t get the same chances

@MavsDraft But even if josh does actually reach his promise..what are the odds he actually reaches it in Dallas if he takes as long as Stephenson does? Dallas has more guard/wing depth than that pacers team had at the time and is under just as much if not more pressure to produce results

@MavsDraft But josh green didn’t just have a bad rookie year. He’s still struggling now, and his promise has shown to be questionable. Where are his opportunities going to come from? Hayward got way more opportunities than green will
@MavsDraft Meanwhile butler ended up being 1) an outlier talent and 2) got to play way more often than the mavs will ever give chances to josh green this year or next year

@MavsDraft Yeah but like, still. It’s kinda weird to be like “well this one late round pick developed late so maybe josh can too!”. The mavs don’t develop players well normally with their top picks because they think they can just draft guys who aren’t ready to be in their rotation
